    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Bulbous perennial lily with a deep, flattened bulb that gives rise to two (rarely three) tongue-shaped, leathery leaves during winter. Leaves lie flat on the ground and are hairy at least along the margins. Leaves dry or absent during flowering season. Flowers borne in January-April on an erect red stem that can be hairy or spotted. This gives rise to 4-5 large scarlet fleshy bracts that from a funnel-shaped structure slightly longer than and surrounding erect, bunched flowers with their prominent yellow stamens.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_9576",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Flowerheads up to about 12 cm tall.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_9577",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Namibia to Cape Peninsula.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_9578",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Confined to coastal sandy habitats along the West Coast, where can form spectacular displays in late summer when the ground is often otherwise bare of vegetation. A popular garden species that attracts pollinating birds and insects. Used in traditional medicine as a diuretic and to treat asthma and stomach complaints, or to dress ulcers and wounds.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_9579",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Photosynthetic.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_9580",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Pollination is by insects and sunbirds. Easily propagated from the soft, translucent berries.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_9581",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Easily recognized to genus, but there are several similar species that occur in the same region. The April fool, <i>H. coccinus,</i> lacks hairs on the leaves and has deep-red spots on the flower stalk, which has 6-9 bracts that are slightly shorter than the flowers.&nbsp; In the Smooth bloodlily, <i>H. sanguineus,</i> the leaves are edged with scarlet hairs and the unmarked red stalk bears 5-11 bracts surrounding a very dense tuft of many flowers.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_9582",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        }
    ],
